Lebanon's Comprehensive Crisis
Beirut — To recall, usually financial crises seem to have omens before they occur; however, they rarely clearly indicate the course of history.
Lebanon's current situation is no different; a foreseeable crisis has plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975–1990), its economic and political systems have been sustained by external borrowing, inevitably leading to the continuous rise of public debt.
At some point, the inflow of external capital had to come to a halt. This turning point arrived in late 2019, followed by a series of consecutive negative shocks.
The "sudden stop" of this capital brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit reaches 25 percent of its gross domestic product, and its export base is too small to even cover the costs of necessary imports.
The second issue is the fiscal situation.
Lebanon's public debt now totals more than 150 percent of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of economic decline, with the budget deficit already substantial at 10 percent of GDP in 2019 and still expanding rapidly.
The most important point is that Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
The major banks, as the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have invested heavily in Lebanese sovereign debt (on average accounting for 50% of their portfolios), and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises have pushed Lebanon's economy into the depths.
Companies that are eager to borrow and import have started laying off workers or closing down completely.
The economic downturn could lead to a Lebanese depression.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political and economic system is not oil, but the diaspora, who are attracted to invest due to high interest rates and the fixed exchange rate pegged to the US dollar.
So it is no wonder that signs of "Dutch disease" are everywhere: deposits have grown to more than 400 percent of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has brought the national savings rate down to an implausibly low level—just 3 percent of GDP.
Inequality is high and rising.
From 2000 to 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50 percent, significantly weakening the tradable sectors.
Due to the lack of export goods and services, Lebanon has been losing its educated youth.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows have allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have siphoned off wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated patronage-based ruling clique.
Although this has ensured political stability in this formerly chaotic region, it has failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is intermittent and unreliable, while the broader macroeconomic challenges remain entirely unresolved.
The financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement took to the streets opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Despite this, the country's regime has so far responded to Lebanon's economic problems overwhelmingly in favor of the elite, indicating that the crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, further consolidating sectarian politics.
For example, the country has refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the major shareholders of each bank, which include ruling politicians, to decide how to quantitatively withdraw cash.
In fact, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens find it difficult to access deposits.
In addition, the central bank reduced deposit rates but has not lowered public debt rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its major foreign debt owed to domestic banks.
There are indications that it may begin selling state-owned assets to elite-connected entities at fire-sale prices.
At the same time, the official exchange rate has remained unchanged, allowing elites to access dollars at a low exchange rate, while ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly declining market exchange rate. The current market exchange rate is now discounted by 40%.
When the country starts printing lira to pay public sector salaries, depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been paying interest on dollar deposits in lira (dollar deposits account for more than 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions for inflation to eliminate public debt.
As the cost of debt reduction is passed on to depositors through the "liraization" of holdings, the banks' capital base is largely spared.
If this situation becomes reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decline in real wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The migration of educated youth will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the diaspora — on which this system relies — will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system that can be controlled by increasingly cheaper shelters.
In the end, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
By contrast, the establishment of a new republic by the revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, patronage, and inequality.
They hope to establish a dynamic high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural power house, and create more synergies with the diaspora.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank capital, and force a 1% reduction in deposits from depositors holding more than 50% of total deposits.
They support a moderate currency devaluation and thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices and increasing spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
Now the infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a broader struggle in the country's search for new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a fatal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future remains uncertain.
